   (Message) The initial segment of the `main()` function in `proj.cpp` checks
   if there are fewer than or equal to one command-line argument (`argc <= 1`).
   If true, it prints a usage message and exits with a status of 0, using
   `exit(0)`. This condition matches the behavior stated in the error
   description: the program exits with code 0 without crashing.
   
   This logic suggests that the program expects certain command-line arguments
   to function correctly. When such arguments are absent, it defaults to
   displaying a help/usage message and terminates with `exit(0)`, which is
   mistakenly interpreted as successful completion instead of an error or misuse
   of the tool.
   
   The actual defect is in failing to adequately distinguish between a usage
   error (which should likely prompt a non-zero exit code indicating improper
   invocation) and successful program execution. This is why the test oracle
   expects a run that doesn't exit with zero, as a meaningful run didn't occur.
   
